if you were abused by someone, im genuinely sorry and you have my sympathy. but im sure we can agree that remembering being hit isnt the same thing as the phenomenon of genuinely being hit. theyre distinct experiences

for instance, i was bashed a few times as a teenager and when i remembered these experiences they were quite alarming. however with time ive come to realise that the emotion and the thought are distinct. the experience and myself arent the same

what happens is that we imagine our self image, then we recollect/imagine a situation in which our self (who is contained in thought) is hurt. theres nothing wrong with remembering harm that has come our way, the only mistake is believing that we are the same entity being hurt in the imagination.

the trauma of being hurt by being abused by someone you trusted is a real physiological phenomenon, we feel fear when we reimagine those scenarios. however, the thought isnt what hurts, its the genuine physical fear we have undergone as a response.

any attempt to pinpoint down a central self is just more thought, more memory and more experience. while we do exist, there isnt a central you that generates thoughts that you can depict within thought itself

the thought i like this thing is a standalone experience. in the same way when you feel a burn, you dont need to imagine who you are as a person to feel the experience of pain. however with thought, we believe that there is more to it then just the sensory stimuli. even though you dont require an imagination of yourself to always be yourself.
